    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Avoiding Foster Care</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by psychotherapist Judith Stein on importance of early intervention and treatment for children who have suffered trauma and loss of parent in early childhood (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Despondent Parents See Foster Care as Only Option'' (news article, Sept. 1):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Despondent Parents See Foster Care as Only Option'' (news article, Sept. 1):</p>
        <p>Early intervention and treatment is important for children who have suffered trauma and loss of a parent in early childhood and for their parents. Such incidents can arrest normal and healthy child development and result in symptoms like anxiety, depression, delinquency, learning  difficulties and problems with interpersonal relationships, including parental ones.</p>
        <p>Parents need to be made aware of the issues that their children are struggling with and the symptoms, and children need therapy to help them deal with these issues. Ideally, in time the children will begin to heal, and drastic measures like foster care can be avoided.</p>
        <p>JUDITH STEIN  New York, Sept. 2, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer, a child psychotherapist, is an adjunct professor at New York University's School of Social Work.</p>
      </block>
